CAVA’s footprint grew nearly 20% in 2025 with 72 net new restaurants. The fast-casual chain anticipates surpassing 500 locations this year with a goal of reaching 1,000 by 2032. During the company’s fourth quarter earnings call Tuesday after market, chief executive officer Brett Schulman said such scaling will come “thoughtfully and sustainably.”&nbsp;

As such, CAVA is sharpening its focus on operations, bolstered by a Flavor Your Future initiative launched in October. The initiative is designed to attract, develop, and retain employees to better support this next phase of growth.

As part of the program, CAVA is adding an assistant general manager role to build a deeper bench. About 60% of AGM roles are now filled, and a majority of them are internal promotions. The entire system is expected to have an AGM in place by the middle of this year.&nbsp;

“While still early, we’re seeing encouraging signs that this approach is having a positive impact,” Schulman said. “Restaurants with AGM coverage are outperforming those without, as AGMs provide additional leadership support during peak dinner and weekend shifts, helping to strengthen execution across every shift, develop future team members, and create more sustainable restaurant teams.”

Schulman added that the pipeline created from the AGM role will help CAVA accelerate growth with “operational integrity.”&nbsp;

The AGMs are coming on board just as Doug Thompson takes over the chain’s chief operations officer role. With his hire, the company is making changes to its field leadership model to further support operator development and “elevate standards.” Those changes include the addition of two zone leaders, reporting directly to Thompson. Schulman said they will split the country to “increase focus, accountability, and leadership proximity to restaurants.”&nbsp;

CAVA also “narrowed the spans of control for its regional leaders.” This, Schulman said, should create more restaurant engagement and consistent coaching. Finally, a new market leader role was added to create a bridge between regional and area leaders and “strengthen day-to-day support and execution at the local level.”&nbsp;

“(We’re) very excited to create a real clear development path and have a developmental system that takes our team members from entering our door as a team member on the line to growing into a multimillion-dollar restaurant leader,” Schulman said.&nbsp;

“The number one priority is that people development pipeline. Number two is elevating our hospitality … in every interaction that every guest has across our restaurants. Lastly, elevate the consistency of how we deliver our operational execution every location, every shift.”

Story Continues

Chief financial officer Tricia Tolivar noted that CAVA’s general and administrative expenses in Q4 rose 10 basis points to reflect these investments, and G&A is expected to remain flat year-over-year given the addition of the two zone leaders and market leader.&nbsp;

“We'll continue to make investments in labor … so that we can create opportunities for our team members so they can deliver on an amazing guest experience,” Tolivar said.&nbsp;

CAVA’s AGM rollout comes on the heels of Starbucks' assistant store manager launch. The coffee giant is looking to add at least one full-time ASM at each location by the end of this year. The idea is the same, according to Starbucks’ chief partner officer, Sara Kelly, who wrote in a blog, “When partners grow, Starbucks grows. That’s the idea behind a new initiative designed to strengthen leadership and unlock new career paths in our coffeehouses.”

"Partner" is how Starbucks refers to its employees.

Popeyes and Wendy’s are also sharpening operations teams following tough quarters. &nbsp;Wendy’s is expanding its field&nbsp;operations&nbsp;team this year to provide more support, coaching, and training. This expansion comes on the heels of an 11.3% same-store sales decline. Meanwhile, Popeyes expanded its U.S. field operations team by 75% following a 4.9% decline in same-store sales in the fourth quarter.&nbsp;

