On the heels of CAVA’s 15th anniversary, chief executive officer and co-founder Brett Schulman made it a point to highlight the fast-casual chain’s recent milestones during its fourth quarter and full-year earnings call Tuesday after market. Those milestones included surpassing $1 billion in revenue and recording the strongest new restaurant opening class to date.&nbsp;

He added that the company’s recent growth, including 24 new restaurant openings during the quarter and 72 during the year, have translated into “meaningful market share gains.”&nbsp;

“We believe our momentum reflects more than just expansion. It signals that our value proposition is resonating with today's increasingly discerning consumer,” Schulman said.&nbsp;

CAVA’s fourth quarter highlights included a 21.2% increase in revenue, to $272.8 million. Same-store sales increased by 0.5% (lapping 21.2% from Q4 2024), driven largely by price. Traffic declined 1.4%. For the full-year, same-store sales were up 4%.

Additionally, restaurant-level profit margin was 21.4%, while adjusted EBITDA (earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation, and amortization) was $25.8 million, and net income was $4.9 million.

Notably, CAVA implemented a 1.4% menu price increase in January, and chief financial officer Tricia Tolivar&nbsp;said no additional price increases are expected this year.&nbsp;

“Today's industry environment is dominated by price discounting, a reflection of many brands who aggressively raised prices in recent years,” Schulman added. “In recent years, we've taken less than half the price increases of industry peers, while underpricing (the Consumer Price Index) by over 10%. It’s these intentional decisions that reinforce trust with our guests and strengthen the long-term foundation of our brand.”&nbsp;

Additional tailwinds&nbsp;

In addition to conservative pricing actions, Schulman also outlined several additional tailwinds creating optimism for the year ahead. CAVA will enter new markets this year across the Midwest, including Cincinnati and Columbus, Ohio, St. Louis, and Minneapolis, with a target of reaching “at least” 1,000 nationwide by 2032. The company finished 2025 with 439 restaurants.

Also, CAVA’s new tiered loyalty program launched in October, has “strengthened engagement” with customers, Schulman said. The chain is building on that program with a new invite-only tier, called Oasis, designed to recognize the most loyal guests and “strengthen long-term relationships.”

Story Continues

“Oasis gives our most engaged members access to enhanced earning opportunities, additional perks, exclusive merchandise, and special events throughout the year,” Schulman said. “This tier is another example of how we will utilize our new loyalty architecture to lean into more tailored and personalized guest experiences over time.”&nbsp;

Further, CAVA will continue its menu innovation with a Pomegranate Glazed Salmon launch toward the end of the first quarter. This marks the chain’s first seafood offer and is a natural extension of the menu, Schulman said.&nbsp;

“Salmon fits seamlessly into the Mediterranean diet and naturally expands the variety of choices we can offer our guests,” he said.&nbsp;

Finally, CAVA continues to realize the benefits of its recently launched Flavor Your Future Initiative, designed to create more development opportunities for employees. As part of this initiative, the chain created an assistant general manager role and has about 60% of those roles filled, a majority of which are internal promotions. Schulman said restaurants with an AGM outperform those without.&nbsp;

CAVA is also changing its field leadership model to better support operator development. This includes the introduction of two zone leaders who will report to new chief operations officer Doug Thompson, as well as a new market leader role.&nbsp;

The chain’s 2026 outlook includes 3% to 5% same-store sales, which Tolivar said is in line with the company’s long-term algorithm.&nbsp;

CAVA Q4 by the numbers&nbsp;

Revenue&nbsp;grew 21.2% to $272.8 million as compared to $225.1 million in the prior-year quarter 24 net new restaurant openings&nbsp; Same-store sales increased by 0.5% Restaurant-level profit&nbsp;of $58.3 million or growth of 15.7% over the prior-year quarter, with&nbsp;restaurant-level profit margin of 21.4 Digital revenue mix was 38.9% Net income&nbsp;of $4.9 million Adjusted EBITDA of $25.8 million compared to $25.1 million in the prior year quarter

